<p>
<seg id=1> Let's have a look at the situation in China. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> The Chinese government recently detained some dissenters once again in order to prevent Chinese Democratic Party members from gathering together in Shanghai, Zhejian province. </seg>
<seg id=3> Voice of America's Chinese report follows, read by Qing Yue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to news put out by the Hong Kong headquarters of the Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy in China, Hangzhou City public security forces took Chinese Democratic Party members Zhu Zhengming and Mao Qingxiang from their respective homes on Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=5> It is currently not known where they are. </seg>
<seg id=6> Before that, the police had detained four key members who were intimately connected with the Chinese Democratic Party. They were Yao Zhenxian, Li Guotao, Wu Yilong, and Wang Rongqing. </seg>
<seg id=7> The Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy in China said that each branch in Shanghai, totaling about twenty members of the Chinese Democratic Party each, had planned to meet on Friday afternoon at a restaurant in Hangzhou City to convene their first meeting. </seg>
<seg id=8> The police arrested them because of the meeting. </seg>
<seg id=9> Public security forces all over Zhejian province warned other democracy activists not to leave their homes to avoid being detained. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Chinese government views the Chinese Democratic Party as an illegal organization, and have detained and interrogated dozens of supporters and activists of the organization. </seg>
<seg id=11> Nevertheless, they are usually quickly released. </seg>
<seg id=12> The Associated Press, Reuters and Agence France Presse have all reported the latest news put out by the Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy in China. </seg>
</p>
